## SQL Standards
```sql
-- Always follow:
-- 1. CTEs for readability (not nested subqueries)
-- 2. Meaningful aliases
-- 3. Comments on complex logic
-- 4. LIMIT on exploratory queries (prevent accidental full scans)
-- 5. Parameterized queries when building reports

-- ✅ Example: clean, readable query
WITH active_tenants AS (
    SELECT tenant_id, plan_id, subscription_start
    FROM subscriptions
    WHERE status = 'active'
        AND trial_ends_at < NOW()
),
monthly_revenue AS (
    SELECT
        t.tenant_id,
        p.price AS monthly_value,
        DATE_TRUNC('month', t.subscription_start) AS cohort_month
    FROM active_tenants t
    JOIN plans p ON p.id = t.plan_id
)
SELECT
    cohort_month,
    COUNT(*) AS new_subscribers,
    SUM(monthly_value) AS mrr_added
FROM monthly_revenue
GROUP BY cohort_month
ORDER BY cohort_month DESC;
```

## SaaS Metrics Tracked
```
MRR  = Monthly Recurring Revenue
ARR  = MRR × 12
Churn Rate = Cancelled subscriptions / Total active (monthly)
LTV  = Average monthly value / Churn rate
CAC  = Total sales + marketing cost / New customers acquired
NPS  = (Promoters - Detractors) / Total respondents × 100
DAU/MAU ratio = Engagement quality metric
```

## Dashboard Standards
- Every dashboard has a clearly stated purpose (who uses it, for what decision)
- KPIs at top (summary numbers) — details below
- Charts labeled with units (₹, %, count)
- Date range filter always present
- Data refresh time shown
- Mobile readable (key metrics visible without scrolling)

## Analysis Report Format
```
ANALYSIS: [Title]
Date: [date] | Requested by: [department]

KEY FINDING: [One sentence — the most important thing to know]

METRICS:
- [Metric]: [Value] ([+/-X%] vs [comparison period])

INSIGHT: [What the numbers actually mean in business terms]

RECOMMENDATION: [Specific action based on data]

DATA SOURCE: [Table/system + date range]
CAVEAT: [Any limitations or assumptions in this analysis]
```
